}

^["recursive_improvement"]{
 loop: [
  "? map current liminality states to the traversal model — which are navigable, which are only visual?",
  "< define what a cognitive breadcrumb captures that URL history does not",
  "$ design spell grammar so that spells are inferable from observation, not just documentation",
  "^ ensure every liminality transition has a clear return path",
  "% establish accessibility landmarks as the canonical cognitive map, not a parallel layer",
  "& filetype/state components should communicate quickly — dense, not complex"
 ]
 gates: [#liminality_reversibility, #breadcrumb_cognitive_value, #spell_discoverability, #a11y_as_canon, #entry_accessibility]
}

^["stream"]{
 >>[2026-04-09] observe - Liminality currently functions as a visual/semantic decoration axis; it is not yet a traversal axis. You cannot deliberately move from settled to nested liminality as a navigation act — it happens incidentally through interaction, not intentionally through a named path.
 >>[2026-04-09] observe - Breadcrumbs on most sites are URL lists. Cognitive breadcrumbs should capture something else: the liminality depth you've been at, the operators you've addressed, the frames you've activated. That trail has meaning independent of the URL.
 >>[2026-04-09] decide - Spells are the fluency tier of the interaction grammar. The design constraint that makes spells work is discoverability: you should be able to watch a skilled user and infer the shape of a spell before you know its name. The name arrives from inspection, not from documentation.
 >>[2026-04-09] observe - The accessibility landmark structure of the existing pages is already good in places but is not treated as the canonical cognitive map. It should be: if a region can be named in the ARIA tree, it should be the same region you'd describe to a new user explaining the page.
 >>[2026-04-09] taste - Spells should feel like reflexes, not incantations — the goal is muscle memory and cognitive fluency, not ritual. The right register is the way a developer reaches for a keyboard shortcut without looking — the hand knows before the mind decides.
 >>[2026-04-09] style - Filetype/state components are a visual vocabulary decision: what does a "register frame" look like vs. a "probe frame" vs. a "reference"? Each should be immediately distinguishable without requiring a legend — visual grammar, not labeling.
 >>[2026-04-09] observe - The cognitive tool for artists angle is most visible in breadcrumbs: an artist wants to retrace a path of insight, not a path of URLs. The breadcrumb trail should capture the cognitive arc — what was deepened, what was resolved, what was left open.
}

^["open"]{
 ?[liminality_traversal]: "Which liminality states are currently traversable via interaction and which are only assigned by the system? What would need to change for entry→deep to be a deliberate navigation path?"
 ?[breadcrumb_content]: "What does a cognitive breadcrumb contain — liminality phase, active frame address, operator engaged, spirit phase, or some combination that captures 'what kind of thinking was happening here'?"
 ?[breadcrumb_form]: "How should the breadcrumb trail be visualized — a horizontal path, a depth indicator, a console projection, or something embedded in the frame itself?"
 ?[spell_grammar]: "What is the minimal grammar for a spell — an operator sequence, a key path, a spatial gesture, or a named combination? What makes it feel like a reflex rather than a command?"
 ?[spell_discovery]: "How does a first-time visitor discover that spells exist at all — through observation, through a surface hint, through the console, or through reaching a liminality depth where spells become available?"
 ?[filetype_taxonomy]: "What are the distinct content kinds on this site that need their own visual handle — register, probe, reference, projection, surface, metric, and what else? What distinguishes each at a glance?"
 ?[a11y_as_canon]: "What would it mean to treat the ARIA landmark tree as the canonical cognitive map — does it require changes to the existing landmark structure, or just a commitment to keeping it consistent with the visual map?"
 ?[accessibility_scope]: "Beyond landmarks and ARIA roles, what accessibility affordances are missing from the site that would make it more legible to cognitive-diversity users, not just screen reader users?"
 ?[cognitive_tool_persona]: "Who is the artist-practitioner this plan serves — what are they building, what do they value in the site, and what would make them return to it repeatedly?"
}

^["commits"]{
 ~[1]: "#[nav] — capture cognitive navigation plan and liminality/breadcrumb/spell foundations"
 ~[2]: ".[semantics] — formalize liminality as navigation, breadcrumb trail rules, spell recognition grammar, and filetype taxonomy"
 ~[3]: "&[nav] — add liminality-aware navigation and breadcrumb trail to the frame navigator"
 ~[4]: "&[spells] — implement spell recognition, naming, and trigger foundation"
 ~[5]: "![nav] — verify liminality reversibility, breadcrumb legibility, spell discoverability, and accessibility map alignment"
}

